R and RStudio

A language for statistical computing and graphics

  • High-level programming language with pre-defined data structures, functions, control structures, …
  • Developed by the R Core Team (since 1997), hosted on CRAN (Comprehensive R Archive Network)
  • Free and available for Windows, Mac, and Linux
  • Download from CRAN

Object-oriented logic

Basic objects

What will we learn?

  • How to create an object (scalar, vector, …)?
  • Naming rules
  • Which types of data can be stored in objects?
  • Attributes of objects
  • How to subset an object?
  • What can we do with an object (unitary and logical operators)?

How to create an object?

  • Objects are created with the assignment operator “<-” (Shortcut: alt -)
my.vec <- c(1, 2)
my.vec
## [1] 1 2
  • Naming rules: Names are not allowed to…
    • begin with a number (not: 1st.vec)
    • contain white spaces (not: my vec)
    • contain reserved words (e.g., “$” or “+”)
  • Names are case sensitive: myVec != myvec

Which types of data can be stored in objects?

  • Three basic types: numeric, character, logical
num.vec <- c(1, 2, 3)
char.vec <- c("a", "b", "c")
logic.vec <- c(TRUE, FALSE, TRUE)

Which types of data can be stored in objects?

Test the type of a vector

class(num.vec)
## [1] "numeric"
is.numeric(num.vec)
## [1] TRUE

Which types of data can be stored in objects?

Test the type of a vector

is.character(num.vec)
## [1] FALSE
is.logical(num.vec)
## [1] FALSE
